<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO Welcomes UN Security Council Resolution 904 </TI></H3>
<H4>   Immediate Implementation Urged </H4>
<F P=102> NC1903175094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1747 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1903175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 19 Mar (MENA)--The PLO has welcomed the UN 
Security Council resolution condemning the al-Ibrahimi Mosque 
massacre in Jerusalem [as received]. 
  An official Palestinian source has affirmed that the 
Security 
Council resolution constitutes a basis for immediate enforcement 
of the measures necessary to protect the Palestinian people in 
the occupied territories in order to guarantee the successful 
resumption of peace negotiations with Israel. 
  Following a meeting under Yasir 'Arafat's chairmanship 
today, 
the PLO called on the international community, particularly the 
sponsors of the peace process, to act immediately to implement 
the Council resolution, because guaranteeing the safety of the 
Palestinian people and international protection for them is an 
essential necessity. The PLO underlined the need to eliminate 
the terrorist pockets in the settlements and to discuss the 
status of armed settlers. 
  The official source noted that the PLO welcomed the issuing 
of the Security Council resolution despite all the difficulties 
and obstacles that were raised to obstruct or avert it. The PLO 
also welcomed the international community's condemnation and its 
endorsement of specific measures to guarantee protection for the 
Palestinian people on their occupied territories, including the 
disarming of settlers and the provision of an international 
presence to protect the Palestinian people. 
  The PLO pointed out that this consensus denotes a public 
awareness of the ugliness of the massacre, its dimensions and 
causes, as well as eagerness to guarantee the safety and 
protection of the Palestinian people. 
  The organization regretted the U.S. abstention on two 
paragraphs on Jerusalem and the occupied territories. It 
affirmed that this attitude affects the U.S. reputation, 
particularly since the issue is related to Jerusalem--a very 
vital issue at the Palestinian, Arab, Islamic, Christian, and 
international levels--and casts doubts on the permanence of 
official U.S. stands on some basic aspects in the regional 
conflict. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

