<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ross Holds Meetings With Palestinians, Israelis </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ross Says Talks `Useful' </H4>
<F P=102> JN2103175694 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1700 GMT 21 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2103175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Muhammad Kurayshan from Tunis] </F>
  [Text] President Yasir 'Arafat and U.S. peace coordinator 
Dennis Ross will resume talks this evening. Following the first 
round of talks this afternoon between'Arafat and Ross, which 
lasted for one and a half hours, Dennis Ross said the meeting 
was useful. However, he did not elaborate. 
  We learned that the meeting focused on listening to the 
Palestinian viewpoint following the issuance of the Security 
Council resolution condemning the Hebron massacre. The 
Palestinian side said that what is required from Washington now 
-- in its capacity as one of the cosponsors -- is to intervene 
effectively to implement the provisions of Resolution 904, 
particularly regarding international protection for the 
Palestinian people under occupation. It cannot just be 
satisfied with listening to the Palestinian and Israeli 
viewpoints but must try to bring them closer. 
  The Palestinian side underscored the need for an 
international security force in the occupied territory, not just 
observers. The Palestinian side also reiterated the need for 
reaching a clear solution to the issue of settlers in Hebron and 
for disarming them. 
  Dennis Ross is expected to meet with the Israeli delegation 
led by Amnon Shahaq before resuming his talks with the 
Palestinian leadership this evening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

