<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Compromise' on Palestinian Security Said Likely </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2103193394 Paris AFP in English 1921 GMT 21 March 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2103193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, March 21 (AFP) -- Israel and the PLO appeared 
headed Monday [21 March] for a compromise on boosting security 
for Palestinians in the occupied territories following the 
Hebron massacre, diplomats said. 
  The compromise proposed by Norwegian Deputy Foreign Minister 
Terje Larsen would allow between 300 and 500 lightly armed 
observers to be deployed in the West Bank town of Hebron, they 
added. 
  Between 600 and 1,000 other observers would be deployed in 
the Gaza Strip, while between 1,100 and 1,200 men would be 
dispatched to Jericho. 
  PLO chief Yasir 'Arafat agrees to the plan so long as it is 
implemented quickly, the diplomats said. 
  The observers, totalling between 2,000 to 2,700 men, would 
conduct joint Israeli-Palestinian patrols under Israeli command. 
  The diplomats said Arafat would likely go to Paris Thursday 
for talks with Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres and for 
discussions with European donors to the financial aid plan for 
the future self-rule authorities. 
  The PLO suspended talks to launch autonomy in Gaza and 
Jericho after a Jewish settler shot dead 30 Arab worshippers at 
the Tomb of the Patriarchs in Hebron last month. 
  The PLO has vowed not to resume the talks until it receives 
adequate security guarantees from Israel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

