<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Says President To Seek Dialogue With FIS </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2103145994 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 19 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2103145994 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Qusayy Salih al-Darwish: "Zeroual To Begin </F>
Dialogue With Salvation Front Next Week"] 
  [Text] Paris -- An Algerian presidential office statement 
issued yesterday said that President Zeroual would start a 
serious and sincere dialogue next week without excluding any 
party, the aim being to end Algeria's crisis and ensure a return 
to elections. It said that dialogue was the preferred way of 
bringing the situation under control. The presidential 
statement also reaffirmed the need for the security forces to 
continue their duties of maintaining public security, 
safeguarding public property, and eradicating violence and 
terrorism. 
  AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned from reliable sources that 
President Zeroual will initiate a dialogue with the leaders of 
the Islamic Salvation Front [FIS] leaders now in prison, Abbasi 
Madani and Ali Belhadj to be specific. These leaders were moved 
from Blida prison the day before yesterday to an unknown place. 
There have been numerous rumors over the past few weeks about 
the transfer of the FIS leaders to a villa somewhere, but the 
report seems to be genuine this time. The sources, who have 
recently been in contact with President Zeroual, quoted him as 
stressing that he assumed the post of president in order to hold 
a genuine dialogue and that he intended to do so. 
  President Zeroual's statement came after the spectacular 
Lambese jailbreak and after the lengthy meetings of the military 
commands. 
  President Zeroual appears to have been able to settle the 
controversy and disagreement in his favor after the recent 
attacks by the hard-line anti-dialogue tendency as reflected in 
the speech delivered by Prime Minister Redha Malek at the 
funeral of playwright Alloula in Oran and in the campaigns of 
the French-language papers criticizing the regime and its 
failure in an attempt to obstruct President Zeroual, forced him 
into a corner, and put him on the defensive. 
  Behind that campaign were the forces which maintain that the 
fundamentalists should be stamped out and the hardline security 
option, not the dialogue option, upheld. 
  Political observers believe that the death sentences handed 
down to six fundamentalists yesterday were part of the attempts 
to embarrass President Zeroual and part of the arm-twisting 
tactics the hard-liners are trying to use. 
  In view of that situation, President Zeroual is expect to 
reshuffle the cabinet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

