<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Reportedly Displeased With 
Jordan Media </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2003161794 Paris AL-MUHARRIR in Arabic 21 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> JN2003161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AL-MUHARRIR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The latest news about Palestinian President Yasir 
'Arafat says the man is angry these days because the Jordanian 
authorities have overlooked the popular media campaign against 
PLO policy and against him personally following the al-Ibrahimi 
Mosque massacre. 
  The Khalil al-Rahman Society and some Palestinian camps near 
Amman recently staged mammoth popular demonstrations, during 
which the demonstrators chanted against the old man ['Arafat] 
and demanded him to cancel the Oslo and Cairo agreements. The 
Jordanian newspapers, both independent and party papers, also 
launched a campaign in which they called for the cancellation of 
agreements with Israel. 
  Abu-'Ammar [Yasir 'Arafat] said during the Palestinian 
leadership's meeting in Tunis that this campaign is directed 
against him personally, as well as the PLO leadership. He 
blamed the Jordanian Government for not quelling the 
demonstrators or preventing columnists from writing against him. 
  AL-MUHARRIR has learned that 'Arafat's anger was about to 
express itself in practice when he proposed transferring 15 
Palestinian leaders from Jordan to Tunisia. However, leading 
Palestinian politicians rejected this proposal and considered it 
an attempt to strain relations with Jordan for no convincing 
reason. The proposal was thus frozen pending discussion in 
future meetings. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

