<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, Opposition Peace Talks To Begin </TI></H3>
<H4>   Opposition Actions Noted </H4>
<F P=102> EA2003173094 Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network in 
Arabic 0430 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA2003173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The peace negotiations between the government and 
the rebel movement will resume in the Kenyan capital of Nairobi 
on 21 March, under the framework of the Intergovernmental 
Authority on Drought and Development [IGADD]. 
  Meanwhile, Dr. 'Ali al-Hajj Muhammad, the official spokesman 
for the government delegation to the peace negotiations, has 
revealed that some elements of the so-called national democratic 
alliance have arrived in Nairobi with the aim of aborting the 
IGADD initiative. During a press conference he held yesterday 
he said he had apprised the Kenyan authorities of this negative 
development, saying that the members of the alliance, who 
represent the opposition parties, aimed at bringing about the 
overthrow of the government and wanted to exploit the issue of 
the south to bring their ambitions to realization, while the 
issue of peace in Sudan was of no concern to them. 
  His excellency appealed to the Kenyan Government to take the 
necessary steps to ensure that the current peace efforts did not 
fail and that the solution should be purely an African one. His 
excellency said that the members of the alliance who had arrived 
in Nairobi were Mubarak al-Fadil al-Mahdi, 'Abd al-Rahman Ahmad 
Sa'id and al-Harith Idris. Dr. 'Ali al-Hajj Hassan said the 
government delegation did not object to their presence provided 
they did so as part of the delegation of the rebel movement. 
  Dr. 'Ali al-Hajj said the entry of foreign quarters or of a 
foreign dimension had always been at the root of failure to 
arrive at an agreement with the rebel movement. His excellency 
appealed to John Garang to throw off foreign hegemony. He said 
the purpose of his convening a press conference was to inform 
the outside world of the facts of what was happening and to 
confirm the eagerness of the government delegation that the 
negotiations should succeed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

