<H3> <TI>   House of Representatives Concludes Session </TI></H3>
<H4>   Al-Majali on U.S. Navy, Ross Visit </H4>
<F P=102> JN2203142494 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1200 GMT 
22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2203142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jamal 'Abbadi from parliament] </F>
  [Excerpts] The royal decree adjourning the ordinary session 
of the 12th Parliament as of tomorrow was read at the beginning 
of the House of Representatives' session today. [passage omitted] 
  The House then discussed several issues that were not on the 
agenda, in particular a proposal presented by 20 deputies 
regarding acts by the U.S. Navy that include obstructing 
al-'Aqabah-bound ships and conducting unjustified inspections of 
these ships. Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali 
commented on this by saying: 
  [Begin al-Majali recording] I met with the U.S. ambassador 
before I came here this morning. I reiterated to him all that 
was in your speech [not further identified] in a very clear way. 
A few weeks ago, we sent a legal memorandum to the Security 
Council to prove this is wrong and illegal. The government is 
following up on this issue. The assistant U.S. secretary of 
state will come [to Jordan] this evening and this issue will 
clearly be on the agenda. During his visit to the United States, 
his majesty the king raised this issue with President Clinton, 
the secretary of defense, and others. In my capacity as the 
prime minister, I went to the committee [not further identified] 
itself and addressed it on this issue with all the strength and 
courage we have. I hope the esteemed House will know that since 
the beginning of this issue the Government of Jordan has taken 
the initiative to deal with it, and even this morning we 
discussed this issue. Thank you. [end recording] [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

