<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shahal Rejects Kakh's Conditions for Surrender </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2103055194 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0500 GMT 21 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2103055194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Police Minister Moshe Shahal has rejected Kakh 
leader Barukh Marzel's conditions for surrendering to police. 
The hunt continues for Marzel. Last night, police detectives 
searched the home in Petah Tiqva of Kakh activist Natan Levi. 
Levi told a Qol Yisra'el reporter that he has no idea where 
Marzel is and that he doesn't think Marzel would hide out at the 
home of someone identified with Kakh. 
  Marzel, who has been in hiding for several weeks, has said 
he 
would turn himself in with the mediation of several Knesset 
members, including Avraham Ravitz of the United Torah Party, but 
Shahal said the law forbids him to respond to such conditions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13924 </DOCNO>
