<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Justice Ministry Rejects Extraditing Dotan, Katz </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2003115494 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 20 Mar 94 p A5 </F>
<F P=103> TA2003115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by defense affairs correspondent Sharon Sade] </F>
  [Excerpts] The Justice Ministry rejects the possibility of 
extraditing Rami Dotan or Attorney Harold Katz to the United 
States if they are convicted by a U.S. court on the basis of the 
charges submitted against them in Ohio at the end of last week. 
  Justice Ministry spokesman Eti Asher explained yesterday 
that 
"Israeli law does not permit the extradition of Israeli citizens 
to foreign countries, even for extraditable offenses. That is 
the reason the United States has not submitted any request for 
the extradition of Rami Dotan and Attorney Harold Katz." 
[passage omitted] 
  Asher added that the United States could request Israel's 
permission to initiate Israeli court proceedings against the men 
named in the charge sheets, if they are indeed convicted by the 
U.S. courts, but it has yet to do so. The United States can 
also demand their extradition from any third country they may 
visit or in which they may reside. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

