<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian-Israeli Meetings Resume in Tunis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2103130494 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 21 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2103130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Muhammad Kurayshan from Tunis] </F>
  [Text] Palestinian-Israeli meetings resumed in Tunis this 
morning. As is known, the Israeli delegation is led by Amnon 
Shahaq while the Palestinian delegation is made up of Dr. Nabil 
Sha'th, Ahmad Quray', and Akram Haniyah. Yesterday, the two 
delegations held a meeting that was also attended by President 
Yasir 'Arafat and Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh. 
  According to Dr. Samir Ghawshah, PLO Executive Committee 
member, the Israeli delegation did not present serious proposals 
on the safety of Palestinians in the occupied territories. What 
he proposed, Ghawshah said, did not meet the minimum 
requirements. This, he added, means practically emptying the 
Security Council Resolution [904] of its substance. 
  Speaking to our radio, the Palestinian official said the 
Israelis had, for example, proposed turning the International 
Red Cross representatives in the occupied territories into 
international observers, according to an Israeli concept of the 
way to implement the Security Council's call for a temporary 
international presence in the occupied territories. It seems 
that during its talks here in Tunis, the Israeli delegation 
showed no positive response to proposals by Norwegian Deputy 
Foreign Minister Larsen on the security measures that should be 
taken in the occupied territories as Yitzhaq Rabin promised in 
his telephone call with Yasir 'Arafat last Friday. 
  U.S. peace coordinator Dennis Ross is due in Tunis this 
afternoon. According to some sources, a quadrapartite meeting 
of the Palestinian and Israeli delegations as well as Ross and 
Larsen is expected to be held to help develop the Israeli 
proposals to protect the Palestinians. It will be according to 
these proposals that the Palestinian stand toward the resumption 
of negotiations will be determined. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-13946 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes055yy_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-055 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ghawshah Says Teams To Resume Talks in Cairo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2203100694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0920 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2203100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 22 Mar (MENA)--PLO Executive Committee member 
Samir Ghawshah has stated that the donor states supporting 
Palestinian self-rule in Gaza and Jericho have agreed to move 
their meeting, which was scheduled to take place in Paris 
Thursday, to Cairo. 
  He told a MENA coprrespondent in Tunis that a Palestinian 
and 
an Israeli delegation will meet on the sidelines of the donor 
states' meeting to continue yesterday's talks in Tunis between 
PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat and an Israeli delegation led by 
Amnon Shahaq, deputy chief of staff and head of the Israeli team 
to the Taba negotiations. 
  Ghawshah said the Israeli delegation promised that during 
the 
Cairo meeting it will reply to some Palestinian questions on the 
transitional international presence in the occupied territories, 
the status of the settlements, and protection for Palestinians 
in the occupied territories. 

</TEXT>

