<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Remark on `Concessions' Seen as `Manuevering' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2203092594 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0545 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2203092594 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the press review] </F>
  [Text] Under the headline "Rabin Is Maneuvering Anew," the 
newspaper AL-BA'TH writes: As part of Israel's policy of 
evading the requirments for peace--and whenever the 
international community tightens the grip on this policy of 
maneuvering and tampering with words--Israel makes statements on 
so-called concessions to this or that party. Rabin has talked a 
great deal about concessions in return for peace with Syria. He 
reiterated this notion of concessions after he returned from 
Washington, supposedly seeking to learn about the nature of 
peace that Syria wants. 
  AL-BA'TH adds: Rabin's remarks are part of an attempt to 
search for a way out of his isolation. At the same time, these 
remarks are a mere semantical game, a much feigned desire for 
peace attempting to cover a strong adherence to occupation. The 
paper points out that anyone who talks about concessions should 
first possess legitimate property or a legitimate right to the 
thing he wants to relinquish. Rabin, as well as the former 
Israeli rulers, do not have any right whatsoever to the occupied 
Arab territories, and thus their alleged concessions are sheer 
falsehood. 
  The paper stresses that the territories are Arab lands with 
legitimate owners whose legitimate rights to these lands have 
been unanimously recognized by the resolutions of international 
legitimacy. The most important of these resolutions are the 
ones on which the peace process was established. Israel, 
however, is evading these resolutions by all ways and means. 
  Concluding, AL-BA'TH says: Rabin is continuing his maneuvers 
and procrastination. This method, however, will not last long 
in view of the available opportunity for peace. This 
opportunity should achieve its objective. 

</TEXT>

