<F P=100> INDIAN VIEWS </F>
<H3> <TI>   BJP President Denounces U.S. `Interference' Over Kashmir </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0103030994 Delhi INDIAN EXPRESS in English 18 Feb 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> BK0103030994 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi INDIAN EXPRESS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] New Delhi -- Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) 
president L.K Advani on Thursday called upon the Government to 
tell the United States in clear and unambiguous language that 
its President Bill Clinton's observations on Jammu and Kashmir 
constituted an "un- friendly" act towards India. It amounted to 
an unwarranted and intolerable interference in the internal 
affairs of the country. 
  Advani reacted to Clinton's recent statements which were 
earlier criticised bv BJP spokespersons and its external affairs 
cell with a view to put the Kashmir issue into focus on the 
national agenda. The observations made by Clinton while 
accepting credentials of the Pakistani ambassador were totally 
against diplomatic norms as such occasions were never used to 
attack a third country, Advani said. 
  He reiterated that Kashmir was an integral part of India and 
the Indian people were confident of safeguarding its territory. 
He said the present US stand on Kashmir was against its earlier 
view in which it had recognised Kashmir as an integral part of 
India. [passage omitted] 
* 

</TEXT>

