<F P=100> PAKISTANI VIEWS </F>
<F P=101> * </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beg Sees U.S. Push for Independent Kashmir </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1602013894 Peshawar THE FRONTIER POST in English 14 Feb 94 
p 10 </F>

<F P=103> BK1602013894 </F>
<F P=104>  Peshawar THE FRONTIER POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Quotation marks as published] </F>
  [Excerpt] General (Retd) Mirza Aslam Beg has further 
elaborated his theory about the `encirclement' of China by the 
United States and the role of Pakistan and India are required to 
play in this programme. He had earlier expressed the view that 
an `independent' Kashmir was being sought by Washington so that 
it could serve as `spying post' against China within the grand 
strategy of `encirclement'. According to him, the continuation 
in force of the Pressler Amendment was a victory of Jewish and 
Hindu lobbies against Pakistan. On the American insistence that 
India and Pakistan should normalise their relations, the general 
is of the view that the two South Asian states are sought to be 
brought together as a par tof the `encirclement' policy by 
Washington. 
  Needless to say, the retired chief of the army staff is 
saying things that people want to hear, given the political 
environment in Pakistan. Because there is such a uniformity of 
intellectual opinion in the country, some rules of debate are 
not being observed, somewhat like the one way debates shown on 
PTV. At the risk of being called Jewish agent, let us look at 
the views expressed by the general who, it must be said in all 
fairness, believes in debate. Would an `independent' Kashmir be 
a good listening post against China when a much less isolated 
Nepal or even Pakistan would be available? What kind of 
`listening' would Washington want in addition to the satellite 
surveillance it already has over China? Would it want to use 
Kashmir militarily when it has missiles that can be delivered 
effectively and probably more accurately from the Indian Ocean? 
[passage omitted] 
* 

</TEXT>

