<F P=103> EA2203203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The peace talks between the Sudanese Government and 
the rebel factions will shortly resume this evening in Nairobi. 
The official session this morning was chaired by the Kenyan 
foreign minister in the presence of the foreign ministers of the 
four Intergovernmental Authority on Drought and Development 
[IGADD] countries. All three negotiating parties, the Sudanese 
Government and the two rebel factions, attended the meeting. 
  It has been resolved that each of the three negotiating 
parties should be represented in the talks by six persons. The 
government delegation stated that the talks would be based on 
previous agendas and start from where the Abuja talks had ended. 
The united faction agrees with the government in this regard, 
but the attitude of Garang's faction towards the previous agenda 
is ambiguous. 
  [Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network in Arabic at 1900 
GMT on 22 March adds: "The peace negotiations between the 
government and the two rebel factions will resume in Nairobi at 
1000 tomorrow with all the delegations continuing to discuss the 
agenda, relief, and other humanitarian issues." 
  ["This evening's session assumed a bilateral form between 
ministers of the IGADD committee and the Sudanese Government 
delegation led by Mr. Muhammad al-Amin Khalifah. During the 
session, the IGADD ministers submitted an agenda derived from 
what had been submitted in the previous peace rounds."] 

