<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Progress Noted in PLO-Israeli Discussions in Tunis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2203163294 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1500 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2203163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] PLO sources announced today that some progress was 
made during the talks between PLO officials and an Israeli 
delegation in Tunis in the past two days. The discussions 
revolved around ways of providing international protection for 
the Palestinians in the occupied territories in line with the 
relevant UN Security Council resolution. 
  The sources added that the meetings between the two sides 
will be resumed in Cairo tomorrow. They pointed out that some 
ideas are being discussed that are likely to result in 
considerable progress. 
  The Israeli delegation members returned to Israel from Tunis 
today to consult with their government. 
  Meanwhile, it has been announced in Oslo that 
representatives 
of the donor countries that will extend aid for Palestinian 
autonomy in Gaza and Jericho will hold a one-day meeting in 
Cairo on Thursday [24 March]. They will discuss ways of 
establishing a Palestinian police force in the occupied 
territories. 
  The Norwegian foreign minister said this step is likely to 
put the Middle East negotiations back on track. 

</TEXT>

