<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Emerging Israel-PLO Agreement Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2303111794 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 23 Mar 94 p 
6 </F>

<F P=103> TA2303111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Shim'on Schiffer and </F>
Tunis correspondent Orli Azulay-Katz] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
and Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres were thoroughly briefed last 
night about the outcome of the talks in Tunis. It has been 
learned that the sides decided on a series of measures to 
protect the Palestinians and increase their sense of security in 
the wake of the massacre in the Cave of the Patriarchs. 
  These are the understandings reached so far: 
  -- An international presence in Hebron, apparently a unit 
made up of a few dozen observers from Norway. 
  -- The establishment of a Palestinian police unit consisting 
of several hundred troops which would deploy in Hebron and would 
be under joint Israeli-Palestinian command. 
  -- Joint patrols to be conducted by Israel, the 
Palestinians, 
and the foreign observers. 
  Palestinian observers in Tunis report on the following 
understandings which have not yet been confirmed by Israel: 
  -- Seven days after the delegations reach a final agreement, 
an armed Palestinian police force will enter the West Bank and 
begin its operations to impose order. 
  -- The trailer neighborhood in the Jericho area will be 
evacuated at once. Three months later, Jewish settlers will be 
evacuated from the heart of Hebron and relocated elsewhere, 
apparently in Qiryat Arba'. Israel has categorically denied 
that it agreed to evacuate the settlers from Hebron. 
  -- All Palestinian deportees will be allowed to return to 
Jericho. 
  -- The PLO leadership will arrive in Jericho a month after 
the deployment of the Palestinian police force. PLO 
administrative personnel and a task force would arrive in the 
area earlier to make all the arrangements for the arrival of the 
leadership. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

