<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Northern Forces Fire Warning Shots at South Fighter Plane </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2203102994 Paris AFP in English 1016 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2203102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, March 22 (AFP)--Northern Yemeni forces fired 
warning shots at a fighter plane from the rival south on Monday 
as it flew low overhead, northern sources said Tuesday. 
  The armies of the former North and South Yemens have not 
merged since the two countries unified in May 1990 and there 
have been frequent clashes between the sides in recent months. 
  The plane was not hit as warning shots were fired as it 
overflew units from the northern al-'Amaliqah [Giants] brigade 
based [in] Abyan, in southern Yemen, the sources said. 
  The country's rival leaders have been involved in a long 
running feud, and tension has risen with the deployment of the 
rival armies in each other's territory. 
  The shooting happened a few hours before a mutual news 
blackout on such incidents was imposed by the two sides. 
  President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih and his ruling General 
People's Congress from the north have been at loggerheads with 
Vice-President 'Ali Salim al-Bid's Yemeni Socialist Party from 
the poorer south for seven months. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

