<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Envoy Ross Arrives in Amman for Brief Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ross, al-'Anani Speak to Reporters </H4>
<F P=102> JN2203205494 Amman Jordan Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2203205494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News at Ten" program] </F>
  [Text] Special Middle East peace coordinator Dennis Ross 
left Amman tonight after talks on the peace process, bilateral 
ties, and the siege of al-'Aqabah. 
  Ross met earlier tonight with Prime Minister 'Abd-al-Salam 
al-Majali, which was followed by bilateral talks between the 
Jordanian and U.S. delegations. 
  Before leaving Amman, Ross said his talks were good and 
businesslike, and that he expects the peace talks to resume soon. 
  Speaking to reporters at Amman airport, Information Minister 
Jawad al-'Anani said tonight's talks also covered the resumption 
of Jordanian-Israeli bilateral talks in Washington, as well as 
economic ties. 
  [Begin recording] [Al-'Anani] We had very good, serious, and 
businesslike discussions today. We covered a range of topics. 
Mr. Ross was kind enough to give us an update on the 
developments in the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations. We also 
dealt with the issue of bilateral issues, like sanctions in 
al-'Aqabah, and also our economic bilateral relations. Well, we 
think that some progress is going to take place very soon, and 
we are going to see tangible results. We also had a discussion 
of how to proceed next on the negotiations, and how to 
invigorate the Jordanian-Israeli track when we meet in 
Washington, hopefully in April. 
  [Unidentified reporter] I would like to ask about the 
Israelis and Palestinians. They said that they agreed on 
international armed presence in Hebron, Gaza, and Jericho. They 
said that the United States and Norway agreed to participate in 
this. Could you elaborate? 
  [Ross] Well, the discussions that they had covered a number 
of areas, including trying to reach understandings on 
security-related issues, and also looking at how one can move 
rapidly to conclude the negotiations and move towards an 
implementation. I am not going to go into the specifics of what 
they are working on right now, because I think their discussions 
are ongoing. 
  [Reporter] I would like to ask you about the siege of 
al-'Aqabah. It is affecting Jordan tremendously. Are you 
going, and do you have any plans to lift the embargo, when? 
  [Ross] Well, we had a discussion. As the minister said, we 
had a discussion on that. We have been exchanging views on 
that. And we are going to be working on that as best we can. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

