<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Envoy Ross Arrives in Amman for Brief Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further on Ross-al-Majali Talks </H4>
<F P=102> JN2303064994 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 0600 GMT 23 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2303064994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Randah Habib report from Amman] </F>
  [Text] In his talks with U.S. coordinator Dennis Ross, 
Jordanian Prime Minister 'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali concentrated on 
the need to lift the naval siege clamped on the port of 
al-'Aqabah three years ago as this siege is adversely affecting 
Jordan's economy. This was emphasized to our station by an 
authoritative source, who added that the talks also dealt with 
the U.S. position on Security Council Resolution 904 on the 
Hebron massacre. Jordan asked Washington to explain its 
abstention from voting on the paragraph which stated that 
Jerusalem is part of the occupied territories and whether this 
abstention constitutes a change in the U.S. position on the holy 
city. 
  The House of Representatives strongly condemned the U.S. 
position on Jerusalem and denounced what it termed the 
continuous U.S. aggression on the Arab nation. It asked the 
Jordanian Government not to return to the negotiations before 
the siege of al-'Aqabah is actually lifted and so announced at 
the Security Council. The deputies said this siege is aimed at 
bringing pressure to bear on Jordan with all possible means to 
deprive it of its free decision vis-a-vis all issues of concern 
to the nation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

