<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Views King's Talks in Oman, Qatar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2203074994 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 22 Mar 94 pp 1, 28 </F>
<F P=103> JN2203074994 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed editorial: "King Husayn's Oman, Qatar Visits"] </F>
  [Text] His Majesty King Husayn's talks in Oman and later 
in Qatar are especially important given Jordan's major pan-Arab 
role in the Arab arena. Oman and Qatar are important players 
both in the Gulf and in the wider Arab arena. 
  King Husayn's Oman visit should further enhance the common 
outlook shared by his majesty and the sultan of Oman on Arab 
issues at this critical point in Arab history, a time when the 
Arabs need to exert themselves in the interest of increased 
solidarity and common understanding. 
  The role being played by Jordan and Oman in the context of 
containing the Yemeni crisis is an indication of a common 
perspective on the challenges facing the Arab nation. This 
makes His Majesty King Husayn's visit to Oman doubly important. 
  His majesty's visit to Qatar is no less important, 
especially 
given that it will be his first since the Gulf crisis, which, if 
it were not for the bold and enlightened stands of such Arab 
states as Qatar, might have torn the fabric of inter-Arab 
relations to shreds. 
  We are optimistic and hopeful that King Husayn's talks in 
Oman and Qatar will yield dividends for a brighter Arab future. 
We are confident that the kind of pan-Arab sense of 
responsibility typical of the courageous leadership in Oman and 
Qatar will go a long way toward furthering Arab solidarity, 
irrespective of the obstacles that have piled up along the way. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

