<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak Discusses Country's Stability, Incidents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2203142594 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1250 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2203142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Remarks by President Husni Mubarak followed by his response </F>
to a question from radio correspondent Muntasir Rahmi on 22 
March; from the "The World on the Air" program--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Mubarak] Egyptian industry really needs no 
testimony from me. A very high percentage of our private sector 
and business sector factories could be exporting their products. 
As long as they export their products, what better testimony do 
they need? [passage omitted] 
  [Rahmi] Do the things you saw during your tour today reflect 
the state of stability in Egypt? 
  [Mubarak] Egypt is stable. Incidents that occur here and 
there are no big issue. Such things happen daily in the world. 
But some parties blow things out of proportion. We also used 
to exaggerate the issue. To increase their circulation, our 
newspapers used to carry banner headlines about incidents not 
worth such headlines. Every day I see incidents happen 
everywhere that are hundreds of times more frequent than the 
incidents in our country. I declare that Egypt is secure and 
stable, despite the minor incidents, which, God willing, will 
disappear. I hope that the youths who accept a little cash to 
do these silly things will regain their senses and realize that 
their actions do not serve the country's interests or their own 
or their families' interests. All industry, investment, 
tourism, and similar projects create jobs for people. When they 
carry out these actions, they are costing people's livelihood. 
Thank you. 
  [Rahmi] Thank you, sir. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

